    <div id=3D"electure-1" class=3D"electure-dialog" style=3D"top:70px;left=
:60px;width:500px;">
  <p>A <strong>Spanning Tree (ST)</strong> of a connected undirected weight=
ed graph <b>G</b> is a subgraph of <b>G</b> that is a <strong>tree</strong>=
 and <strong>connects (spans) all vertices of <b>G</b></strong>. A graph <b=
>G</b> can have many STs (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cayl=
ey%27s_formula" target=3D"_blank"><u>this</u></a> or <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Kirchhoff%27s_theorem" target=3D"_blank"><u>this</u></a>=
), each with different total weight (the sum of edge weights in the ST).</p=
><br><p>A <strong>Min(imum) Spanning Tree (MST)</strong> of <b>G</b> is an =
ST of <b>G</b> that has the <strong>smallest total weight</strong> among th=
e various STs.</p>

<div class=3D"electure-addition">
